value.value: Any electronic or written record of clinical observations.
A Health Level 7 specification containing the structure and semantics that clinical documents should follow in order to facilitate data exchange.
Any physical or virtual contact between a patient (or trial subject) and healthcare provider at which an assessment or activity takes place.
A state of uncertainty regarding the therapeutic advantages of one treatment over another.

The extent to which the findings of a clinical trial can be reliably extrapolated from the subjects who participated in the trial to a broader patient population and a broader range of clinical settings. (ICH)

Any haplorhine primate not belonging to the family Tarsiidae, Hylobatidae, Pongidae, or Hominidae; this does not correspond to any taxon. This group is divided into Old World monkeys (Cercopithecidae) and New World monkeys (Callitrichidae and Cebidae).  Many types are used as an experimental model for human disease and drug testing.

Any experiment that involves a test article and one or more human subjects, and must either meet the requirements for prior submission to the FDA or the results of which are to be submitted to or inspected by the FDA later as part of an application for a research or marketing permit.
A discrete piece of clinical information represented in a way that humans or machines can understand and interpret.
A laboratory that analyzes patient or subject samples collected as part of healthcare treatment or clinical research.

label.value: Clinical Outcomes Assessment Concept of Interest

value.value: The characteristic or variable that is measured in a clinical outcome assessment.

label.value: Clinical Outcomes Assessment Context of Use

value.value: A description of the purpose and criteria for use of a clinical outcome assessment.
The development and testing of a drug, device, or therapy in human subjects to determine safety and efficacy.
A planned activity within a clinical study that marks a transition between epochs or elements within the clinical study.
A data element associated with a clinical study.
The responsibility assumed by a person administering any activities within a clinical study.

A written description of a study of any therapeutic, prophylactic, or diagnostic agent conducted in human subjects, in which the clinical and statistical description, presentations, and analysis are fully integrated into a single report. (ICH E6)
Type C retroviruses that cause leukemia in mice.  Includes the Abelson, AKR, Friend, Moloney, Gross, and other leukemia viruses.
Authorization from an regulatory agency to undertake a clinical trial.
Information collected during the course of a scientifically-controlled study of the safety and efficacy of a therapeutic agent, such as a drug or vaccine, using consenting human subjects.

The act of concluding participation by an enrolled subject prior to completion of all protocol-required elements in a trial. NOTE: Four categories of discontinuation are distinguished: a) dropout: Active discontinuation by a subject (also a noun referring to such a discontinued subject); b) investigator initiated discontinuation (e.g., for cause); c) loss to follow-up: cessation of participation without notice or action by the subject; d) sponsor initiated discontinuation. Note that subject discontinuation does not necessarily imply exclusion of subject data from analysis. "Termination of subject" has a history of synonymous use, but is now considered nonstandard. [After ICH E3, section 10.1 and FDA Guidance for Industry: Submission of Abbreviated Reports & Synopses in Support of Marketing Applications, IV A]
A subject who stops participating in a clinical trial before the last visit or observation that is required by the study protocol.
A process that allows sponsors to apply for approval for each clinical study while granting an exemption from the requirement to hold a clinical trial certificate (CTC).
Any and all information related to a clinical study, including study or trial data, data integrity information, and administration.

The act by a regulatory authority(ies) of conducting an official review of documents, facilities, records, and any other resources that are deemed by the authority(ies) to be related to the clinical trial and that may be located at the site of the trial, at the sponsor's and/or contract research organization's (CRO's) facilities, or at other establishments deemed appropriate by the regulatory authority(ies). (ICH)
A term of art referring to the entire set of goods and equipment that are given to a researcher by the trial sponsor, in order to carry out the clinical trial.

A type of paramyxovirus. It spreads from person to person through coughs, sneezes and saliva, as well as through contact with contaminated items and surfaces. Once the mumps virus enters the body, it passes into the bloodstream and can spread to many different glands and to the brain.
The main purpose of an investigation that can be measured objectively to determine whether the treatment or intervention being studied is beneficial.

A document that describes the objective(s), design, methodology, statistical considerations, and organization of a trial. The protocol usually also gives the background and rationale for the trial, but these could be provided in other protocol referenced documents. Throughout the ICH GCP Guideline the term protocol refers to protocol and protocol amendments. NOTE: Present usage can refer to any of three distinct entities: 1) the plan (i.e., content) of a protocol, 2) the protocol document, and 3) a series of tests or treatments (as in oncology). [ICH E6 Glossary]

A publicly available database of clinical trial summary information, which may include purpose of the study, recruiting status, condition and medical product under study, study design, trial phase, participation criteria, contact information, primary outcome measure, and results.
An assessment from a qualified medical professional based on examination of a subject's health status.
A list of standard terms and meanings that represent the allowable values for a data item.
The process of testing an instrument or patient questionnaire with target populations to see if it is understood as intended by the creators of the tool.
Private information from clinical documents that, if allowed to become public, would impair the genuine financial interest of the company who holds the application.
A type of trial in which the drug of interest is compared against another drug or placebo.
An investigational or marketed product (i.e., active control), or placebo, used as a reference in a clinical trial. (ICH)
An individual or entity whose business is to supply computer systems or software to the consumer.
Taxonomic family which includes mice, rats, and gerbils.
A type of phase 3 clinical trial in which the previously characterized actions of a therapeutic intervention, in an earlier phase trial, are verified.
The means by which regulated products are determined to meet the standards of the European Medicine Agency's Essential Requirements.
An official of the Food and Drug Administration who coordinates the review process of sponsor applications.
Planned response to an anticipated but conditional event in a clinical trial. (CDISC)
The process by which electronic records are created and maintained in a database for regulated clinical investigations such that the data can be considered adequate and accurate.
A committee that a sponsor may organize to coordinate the conduct of a multicenter trial. (ICH)
The number of active and former participants.
The number of active participants.
Ability of a patient or subject to successfully perform tasks required for daily living.
Information input into a systematic, automated format from another device or automated source.
A retro-transcribing virus, of the genus Alpharetrovirus and the family Retroviridae, that causes anemia and malignant disease in wild and domestic fowl.
